Survivial Analysis of Lung Cancer

Yifan Yang

Aim

This research aims to elucidate the concept of survival analysis, highlighting the differences in methodologies and test statistics employed in the examination of survival data.

datasets

This study will be using the Veterans Administrative Lung Cancer dataset(R Dataset) of 137 patients having advanced inoperable Lung cancer, carried out by the US Veterans Administration.

The factors included in the dataset are:

  • trt: 1=standard 2=test
  • celltype: 1=squamous, 2=smallcell, 3=adeno, 4=large
  • time: survival time
  • status: censoring status
  • karno: Karnofsky performance score (100=good)
  • diagtime: months from diagnosis to randomisation
  • age: in years
  • prior: prior therapy 0=no, 10=yes

log Rank test

The Log Rank test stands as one of the most widely adopted methods in survival analysis. It evaluates both the observed and expected number of events (failures) and establishes a chi-square statistic to test the null hypothesis. This test is applicable when the hazard rates between two groups run parallel.

survdiff(Surv(time, status)~trt, data=veteran)
## Call:
## survdiff(formula = Surv(time, status) ~ trt, data = veteran)
## 
##        N Observed Expected (O-E)^2/E (O-E)^2/V
## trt=1 69       64     64.5   0.00388   0.00823
## trt=2 68       64     63.5   0.00394   0.00823
## 
##  Chisq= 0  on 1 degrees of freedom, p= 0.9

More beatiful and easy graph can be made using survminer

ggsurvplot(
  km.model2,
  legend.labs = c("standard", "test"),
  legend.title = "Treatment",
  title = "KM-Model",
  
  xlab = "Time (Days)",
  ylab = "%Alive = S(t)",
  # Add p-value and tervals
  pval = TRUE,
  log.rank.weights = "1",# weights=1 corresponding to log-rank test
  
  conf.int = TRUE,
  # Add risk table
  risk.table = TRUE,
  tables.height = 0.2,
  tables.theme = theme_cleantable(),
  surv.median.line = "hv",  # add the median survival pointer.
  
  
  palette = c("#E7B800", "#2E9FDF"),
  ggtheme = theme_bw() # Change ggplot2 theme)
)

Kaplan Meier survival curves were constructed for both treatment showed almost identical survival pattern and has p-value much larger than 0.05, indicating there is no significant effects.

Wilcoxon test

Unlike the Log Rank test, Wilcoxon test method operates on the principle that the exponentiated coefficient [Exp(B)] for the two groups need not remain constant, thus particularly well-suited for analyzing early failures in survival data.

ggsurvplot(
  km.model2,
  legend.labs = c("standard", "test"),
  legend.title = "Treatment",
  title = "KM-Model",
  
  xlab = "Time (Days)",
  ylab = "%Alive = S(t)",
  # Add p-value and tervals
  pval = TRUE,
  log.rank.weights = "n",# weights=n corresponding to generalized Wilcoxon test
  
  conf.int = TRUE,
  # Add risk table
  risk.table = TRUE,
  tables.height = 0.2,
  tables.theme = theme_cleantable(),
  
  ncensor.plot = TRUE,      # plot the number of censored subjects at time t
  surv.median.line = "hv",  # add the median survival pointer.
  
  palette = c("#E7B800", "#2E9FDF"),
  ggtheme = theme_bw() # Change ggplot2 theme)
)

regression model

Kaplan-Meier model is a non-parametric method. Here we test the results on a parametric model.

exponential model

Using the Concept of exponential distribution, where \[ s(t) = P(T > t) = 1 - F(t) = e^{-\lambda t} \]

The hazard rate, represented by \(\lambda\), is calculated using the formula:

\[\lambda = e^{(b_0 + b_1 X_1 + b_2 X_2 + \ldots + b_k X_k)}\]

Exponential model fit with all covariates

em <- survreg(Surv(time, status) ~ trt + celltype + karno + diagtime + age + prior , 
              data = veteran, dist = "exp")

Cox Proportional Hazards Model

This model benefits by allowing Harvard to change over time, but hazard ratio between different groups is constant.

If we fit Cox Proportional Hazards Model against treatment

cox <- coxph(Surv(time, status) ~ trt, data = veteran)

summary(cox)

exp(coef) can be interpret as at a given instant in time, person who in this circumstance is exp(coef) likely to die with adjusting for other factors.

With exp(coef) close to 1 and p values much larger than 0.05, people with test treatment and people with standard treatment does not have significanly difference in survival rate. Agree with previous results.

Check the assumption of Cox Proportional Hazards Model

While the Cox Proportional Hazards model is thought to be robust, we need to check the underlying assumptions. The violation of assumptions indicate the inaccuray of model results.

  1. check linearity
plot(predict(cox2), residuals(cox2, type="martingale"),
     xlab="fitted values", ylab="martingale residuals",
     main="residual plot", las=1)

abline(h=0)

lines(smooth.spline(predict(cox2), residuals(cox2, type="martingale")),
                    col="red")

we can valid the linearity of the data.

  1. check the proportional hazards assumptions (PH assumption)

Using Schoenfeld test. H_0: Hazards are proportional.

cox.zph(cox2)
##            chisq df       p
## trt       0.2644  1 0.60712
## celltype 15.2274  3 0.00163
## karno    12.9352  1 0.00032
## diagtime  0.0129  1 0.90961
## age       1.8288  1 0.17627
## prior     2.1656  1 0.14113
## GLOBAL   34.5525  8 3.2e-05
par(mfrow=c(2,3))
# Loop through each plot
for(i in 1:6) {
  # Generate the plot using cox.zph()
  plot(cox.zph(cox2)[i])
  
  # Add a horizontal line at h=0 with red color
  abline(h=0, col="red")
}

The graph demonstrate if we allowed the hazard to change overtime.

The solid line represents if we allow change, how hazard will change.

The graph for the karno deviate from zero, may indicating the violation of PH assumption. We could stratified this parameter, or use time-depends coefficient model, allowing hazard change overtime.

Aalens additive hazards model

Aalens additive hazards model is a method that can be used as an alternative to the Cox proportional hazards model when the proportional hazards (PH) assumption is violated. When the PH assumption is not met, the relationship between the predictor variables and the hazard rate may change over time, and this can lead to biased or misleading results if using the Cox model.

Aalens additive hazards model allows for the coefficients of the predictors to vary over time, thereby accommodating non-proportional hazards.

The Aalen model assumes that the cumulative hazard H(t) for a subject can be expressed as a(t) + X B(t), where a(t) is a time-dependent intercept term, X is the vector of covariates for the subject (possibly time-dependent), and B(t) is a time-dependent matrix of coefficients.

aa_model <-aareg(Surv(time, status) ~ trt + celltype + karno + diagtime + age + prior ,                  data = veteran)
